100 :)

pred ≜ λn.

*~*~* stuff *~*~*

(slide "pred")
------------------------------------------------------------
replace f with something that takes (a, b) to (a + 1, a)
replace x with (0, 0)

so like,
(0, 0)
(1, 0)
(2, 1)
(3, 2)
...

then pick the second part of the pair to get previous number
------------------------------------------------------------

pair ≜ λa.λb.λf.f a b
pair :)

pair foo bar
(λa.λb.λf.f a b) foo bar
(λb.λf.f foo b) bar
(λf.f foo bar) (λa.λb.a)
(λa.λb.a) foo bar
(λb.foo) bar
foo

fst ≜ λp.p (λa.λb.a)
fst :)

fst (pair foo bar)
(λp.p (λa.λb.a)) ((λa.λb.λf.f a b) foo bar)
(λa.λb.λf.f a b) foo bar (λa.λb.a)
(λb.λf.f foo b) bar (λa.λb.a)
(λf.f foo bar) (λa.λb.a)
(λa.λb.a) foo bar
(λb.foo) bar
foo

snd ≜ λp.p (λa.λb.b)
snd :)

snd (pair foo bar)
(λp.p (λa.λb.b)) ((λa.λb.λf.f a b) foo bar)
(λa.λb.λf.f a b) foo bar (λa.λb.b)
(λb.λf.f foo b) bar (λa.λb.b)
(λf.f foo bar) (λa.λb.b)
(λa.λb.b) foo bar
(λb.b) bar
bar

(slide "pred")
------------------------------------------------------------
replace f with something that takes (a, b) to (a + 1, a)
replace x with (0, 0)

so like,
(0, 0)
(1, 0)
(2, 1)
(3, 2)
...

then pick the second part of the pair to get previous number
------------------------------------------------------------


predhalp ≜ λp.pair (S (fst p)) (fst p)
predhalp :)

6 ≜ λf.λx.f (f (f (f (f (f x)))))
6 :)

*~*~* stuff *~*~*

(slide "numlist1")
------------------------------------------------------------
list:
(cons 1 (cons 2 (cons 3 nil)))
number:
(S (S (S 0)))
------------------------------------------------------------

(slide "numlist2")
------------------------------------------------------------
so numbers are basically lists, but without junk in them:

             junk
       _______|_______
      |       |       |
      v       v       v
(cons 1 (cons 2 (cons 3 nil)))


(s      (s      (s      0))) 
      ʌ       ʌ       ʌ
      |_______|_______|
              |
           no junk
------------------------------------------------------------

0 ≜ λf.λx.x
S ≜ λn.λf.λx.f (n f x)

nil ≜ λc.λn.n
nil :)

cons ≜ λh.λt.λc.λn.c h (t c n)
cons :)
cons :)

cons foo nil
(λh.λt.λc.λn.c h (t c n)) foo (λc.λn.n)
(λt.λc.λn.c foo (t c n)) (λc.λn.n)
λc.λn.c foo ((λc.λn.n) c n)
λc.λn.c foo ((λn.n) n)
λc.λn.c foo n

cons foo (cons bar (cons quux nil))
(λh.λt.λc.λn.c h (t c n)) foo ((λh.λt.λc.λn.c h (t c n)) bar ((λh.λt.λc.λn.c h (t c n)) quux (λc.λn.n)))
(λt.λc.λn.c foo (t c n)) ((λh.λt.λc.λn.c h (t c n)) bar ((λh.λt.λc.λn.c h (t c n)) quux (λc.λn.n)))
λc.λn.c foo ((λh.λt.λc.λn.c h (t c n)) bar ((λh.λt.λc.λn.c h (t c n)) quux (λc.λn.n)) c n)
λc.λn.c foo ((λt.λc.λn.c bar (t c n)) ((λh.λt.λc.λn.c h (t c n)) quux (λc.λn.n)) c n)
λc.λn.c foo ((λc.λn.c bar ((λh.λt.λc.λn.c h (t c n)) quux (λc.λn.n) c n)) c n)
λc.λn.c foo ((λn.c bar ((λh.λt.λc.λn.c h (t c n)) quux (λc.λn.n) c n)) n)
λc.λn.c foo (c bar ((λh.λt.λc.λn.c h (t c n)) quux (λc.λn.n) c n))
λc.λn.c foo (c bar ((λt.λc.λn.c quux (t c n)) (λc.λn.n) c n))
λc.λn.c foo (c bar ((λc.λn.c quux ((λc.λn.n) c n)) c n))
λc.λn.c foo (c bar ((λn.c quux ((λc.λn.n) c n)) n))
λc.λn.c foo (c bar (c quux ((λc.λn.n) c n)))
λc.λn.c foo (c bar (c quux ((λn.n) n)))
alist ≜ λc.λn.c foo (c bar (c quux n))
alist :)

(slide "foldquote")
------------------------------------------------------------
In fact, a data structure can be faithfully represented by -- is isomorphic to -- its right fold. For example, the entire list processing library, from head and tail to drop and take and even zipWith can be written entirely in terms of foldr.
http://okmij.org/ftp/Haskell/AlgorithmsH1.html#foldl
------------------------------------------------------------

(slide "listfolds")
------------------------------------------------------------

   fold + 0 (cons 1 (cons 2 (cons 3 nil)))

appendy:

a = (cons 1 (cons 2 nil))
b = (cons 3 (cons 4 nil))

   fold cons b a
=> fold cons b (cons 1 (cons 2 nil))
=>             (cons 1 (cons 2 b))
=>             (cons 1 (cons 2 (cons 3 (cons 4 nil))))
------------------------------------------------------------


(slide "numfold")
------------------------------------------------------------
so folding a number would be like,

a = S (S (S 0))
b = S (S 0)

plus:
   fold S b a
=> fold S b (S (S (S 0)))
=>          (S (S (S b)))
=>          (S (S (S (S (S 0)))))

mult:
   fold (+ b) 0 a
=> fold (+ b) 0 (S (S (S 0)))
=>              (+ b (+ b (+ b 0)))
=>              (+ (S (S 0)) (+ (S (S 0)) (+ (S (S 0)) 0)))
...
=>              (S (S (S (S (S (S 0))))))
------------------------------------------------------------
